        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>New Orleans</placeName>
                <date>Sept. 1. 1848</date>.</p>
            <p>Dr Sir.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I received your dated <date>Aug 14</date> &amp; now hasten to
                answer<lb/> it as I have in part <sic>attented</sic> to your commands. <persName>Mr.
                    Lerg</persName> states<lb/> that you promised <hi rend="underline">twelve</hi>
                numbers &amp; in as much as you reduced<lb/> it to <hi rend="underline">five</hi>,
                the subscribers became disgusted &amp; were crying out<lb/> against it to him. Not
                to be tormented by impertinent questions<lb/> he sent the box of undistributed
                numbers to my brother &amp;<lb/> they are now at my father's store awaiting your
                orders.<lb/> I would do well to state something relative in the “Occident”<lb/>
                &amp; let me know what course to pursue. The congregation<lb/> have as yet given me
                no answer, as respects the Books.<lb/> Father states <persName>Mr.
                    Wright's</persName> account shall be <sic>attented</sic> to<lb/> &amp; he makes
                himself responsible. <persName>Dr. Luzenburg's</persName> executor<lb/> acknowledges
                the accounts I shall shortly send in the<lb/> bill. <persName>Mr. G.
                    Jonas</persName> got a set of the Pentateuch but preferred<lb/> for use, the
                sheep gilt at $13 of which there were<lb/> two set, farther took the other. Let me
                know if <persName>Mr.<lb/> B. B. Hart</persName> has paid you. There is about $40 of
                yours<lb/> now in my hands counting the $13 of <persName>Mr. Jonas</persName>.<lb/>
                I think that you had better state in the 'Occident'<lb/> also that the Books are for
                sale by me &amp; that will<lb/> save the advertisement &amp; have still the same effect.<lb/>
                <persName>Mr. Marks</persName> will return me an answer soon.</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>I think <persName>Mrs Florance</persName> has already procured a set<lb/> as you
                state. <persName>Mr. Newton</persName> will decline paying I<lb/> think he is at the
                    <placeName>north</placeName> now, that is for<lb/> those number he asked, try
                &amp; see him yourself<lb/> while he is in <placeName>Phila.</placeName> You gave me
                no answer<lb/> as to the disposal of that fine set of Prayer Books<lb/> at $33.00,
                does your silence approve or disapprove?<lb/> Acknowledge the receipt of
                    <persName>Mr. Touro</persName> for vol IV.<lb/>
                <persName>J. Rodriguez</persName> for vol IV. <persName>Newton</persName> for IV
                &amp; V <persName>Sampson</persName> for<lb/> IV. V. &amp; VI.
                    <persName>Philips</persName> IV &amp; V as I have collected said amounts.<lb/> I
                shall shortly begin to correspond with you, given<lb/> you a description of the
                progression of the Jews<lb/> in the city in relation to religious duties,
                should<lb/> you think proper to allow them a place in the “Occident”<lb/> I shall be
                much obliged to you my signature<lb/> shall be 'Z'. The synagogue is fast
                    <sic>progression</sic>,<lb/> whose description shall be one of the themes<lb/>
                of my communications. With this I think you are<lb/> sufficiently acquainted with
                your southern affairs.</p>
            <p rend="indent(6)">&amp; I remain yrs.</p>
            <p rend="indent(6)">
                <persName role="author">Hen. S. Labatt</persName>
            </p>
